The statement follows the recent doping investigation into 15-year-old Russian skater, Kamila Valieva and the last year’s scandal on Nigerian sprinter, Blessing Okagbare, who was hit with three separate anti-doping charges. He says athletes need to be aware of the various health scare if one is found using substances. “They need to realize that doping substances, some are either medication that are prescribed for animals, so you can imagine what happens when someone that is very healthy and has no therapeutic requirements start to take substances that are meant for  animals. “There are substances that could to kidney failure, cardiac failure and into depression.” Besides doping being a sport issue, it is also a public health problem. By using these substances that are prohibited in the health list, one has a potential of severe health implications. He says to make sure there are anti-doping programmes they recently met with Ministers of Sport from different regions in Africa to advices on the matter. Swigelaar added that the organisation has seen a lot of co-operation between different countries and regions. According to Swigelaar, WADA continues to be part of the global system that is investing money in different regions such as Africa, Asia and Latin America and to ensure that anti-doping system is enhanced and developed. He indicated that there’s a concerned in Africa that there’s not much testing happening. “The continent is not investing enough into testing to prove that our athletes are clean.” However, WADA is supporting the development of Regional Anti-doping Organisation with different countries to assist with the challenges they are experiencing. For full interview click audio below: --Bomkazi Malobola/ ChannelAfrica--